article.headline: Big Dog continues to lead Hawks' charge
article.linkText: Big Dogs: Hawks drop Nuggets for third straight win
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- So much for the early-season theory that the Atlanta Hawks' success was tied to Glenn Robinson reaching 30 points. Robinson was held below 30 points for the first time this season, but the Hawks still gained their third straight victory by defeating the Denver Nuggets 103-87 Tuesday night. "Glenn gave us what we needed, got us points when we needed them,'' Atlanta coach Lon Kruger said. "The difference is we have a nice supporting cast with Shareef (Abdur-Rahim) and Alan (Henderson) and they provide a nice complement.'' Robinson, who scored 34, 30 and 30 in Atlanta's first three games, had 23 points on 9-for-18 shooting. Abdur-Rahim added 19 points and 12 rebounds. "I think I'm always going to want the ball in a tight situation but we still have other guys that can make shots,'' Robinson said. "Shareef is a very experienced player and has been in that situation before, as well as JT (Jason Terry).'' Alan Henderson scored seven of his 17 points and Dion Glover had 10 of his 14 in the fourth quarter when the Hawks pulled away. Juwan Howard led Denver with 25 points and 15 rebounds. James Posey had 21. The Nuggets were 23-of-28 from the line after making their first 10 free throws. "I thought early in the game we couldn't make a basket and they made every shot,'' Posey said. "We fought our way back, but the turning point came when we missed layups and they came back and scored.'' Robinson put the Hawks ahead by three with the first points of the final period. Ryan Bowen's free throw made it 80-78, but Henderson began a 10-1 run with a layup and Terry finished it with a 3-pointer with 6:15 left to put Atlanta ahead 90-79. "I'm always ready to pass to the open man,'' Robinson said. "The team that can pass is the team that is going to win, and I know that I'm going to get plenty of opportunity to shoot the ball and have a lot of shots.'' Chris Anderson got Denver as close as 90-81 with a rebound basket, but Glover sealed the win five straight points. "We were standing around a bit when Alan and Dion stepped it up,'' Kruger said. "Those two made the difference in the fourth quarter.'' After trailing by 15 at the break and 20 prior to that, a 19-2 run keyed by six of Posey's 10 points in the quarter brought Denver back. Howard's tip with 2:01 tied the game at 70. Atlanta took advantage of Denver's 1-for-10 start to a 13-2 lead after a dunk and a 3 by Abdur-Rahim. Howard matched Abdur-Rahim with eight points in the period and helped close the gap to 25-18 by the end of the first quarter. "We were simply manhandled from the start,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "I told our players after the game that this is a league of men and they had to play like men at all times.''

Game notes
Atlanta is 9-20 in Denver. The Hawks have won the last four meetings and were the first team to score 90 points against the Nuggets. ... Howard played his first game of the year after serving a two-game suspension then missing Saturday game at Portland with a stomach virus. ... The Nuggets began their first of two four-game homestands. ... The Nuggets have held opponents below 20 points in seven of 16 quarters. ... Chris Whitney left the game late in the fourth quarter with a sprained left ankle.
